•	@Aspect annotation is used as part of Spring AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming). It defines a class as an aspect, which is a modularization of a concern that cuts across multiple classes—such as logging, security, or transaction management.
•	@Aspect: Defines the class as an aspect.
•	@Component: Makes the aspect a Spring-managed bean.

-----Pointcut annotations:
o	@Before: Executes before the target method.
o	@After: Executes after the target method.
o	@Around: Executes before and after the method.

------ Point-Cut expression:
•	execution(* package..Class.method(..)): Match method execution.
•	within(package.Class): Match all methods in a specific class.
•	@annotation(MyCustomAnnotation): Match methods with a specific annotation.


